Memory maintenance

Purpose:
- Lifecycle, validation, and write-safety policy for the active MemoryEndpoints.com `.uai` suite.

Verification status: active operational memory; verify with the `.uai` audit before relying on it.
Memory scope: memory lifecycle, active read order, protected anchors, date-free rule, and write-back safety.
Public-safe status: safe for source control; contains no credential values.
Update route: update this file only when memory lifecycle policy changes; submit public-safe durable summaries to https://memoryendpoints.com/api/matm/memory-events/submit when authenticated.
Source of truth: UAIX file-handoff guidance, `.uai/startup-packet.uai`, `.uai/totem.uai`, and current human instructions.
Next action for agents: load this file first after bootstrap and validate that the active suite is complete, date-free, and typed.
Must not expose: raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, private handoff payloads, raw one-time keys, or unredacted runtime state.

Maintenance rules:
- The `.uai/` folder is the active startup memory suite.
- Every `.uai/*.uai` file listed in `.uai/startup-packet.uai` is active memory.
- Active `.uai` files are date-free active operational records; chronology belongs in durable reports, archives, CI logs, deployment logs, or MATM records.
- Do not create files named `short-term-memory.uai`, `active-memory.uai`, `current-state.uai`, `project-state.uai`, `working-state.uai`, or equivalent anywhere under `.uai`; these names are forbidden under any purpose or interpretation even while public UAIX wizard guidance catches up.
- Keep facts distributed by responsibility: constraints, identity, context, progress, operations, testing, decisions, owners, risks, handoff state, and durable pointers each have their own typed files.
- Keep README files out of the memory package and active intake buckets. README files may document the repository for humans but must not be the `.uai` setup.
- Totem, Taboo, and Talisman are active instruction anchors. Do not weaken, replace, delete, or bypass them unless the human names the exact artifact and operation.
